article.description: Wally  Szczerbiak had 22 points in the Wolves' 107-86 victory over the Warriors on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Szczerbiak the spark for Timberwolves
article.linkText: T-Wolves have easy time whipping Warriors
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- With two seconds left in the first half, Kevin Garnett took an inbound pass after a Golden State turnover and tapped the ball to Wally Szczerbiak, who nailed a 3-pointer to give Minnesota a 60-50 lead. The basket only accounted for three of Szczerbiak's 22 points in the Wolves' 107-86 victory over the Warriors on Tuesday night. But to Golden State, it was the turning point of the game. "We had mind-lock in the last few seconds. That kind of put a damper on it," said Warriors coach Dave Cowens, whose team had kept pace with Minnesota for much of the first half and pulled to 55-50 with 22 seconds left. "They used that 10-point lead at halftime to their advantage. We couldn't get around it," Larry Hughes said of Szczerbiak's shot. It was all Minnesota in the second half. The Wolves, who never trailed, opened the fourth quarter with a 10-2 run to go up 89-68. Minnesota opened its biggest lead when Chauncey Billups hit consecutive 3-pointers to make it 97-75 with 4:01 remaining. Billups scored nine of his 11 points in the fourth quarter, and Gary Trent had eight of his 14 in the period. "That's what we want, for guys on the bench to be able to carry us in the fourth quarter and that's what they did tonight," said Szczerbiak, who had 20 points in the first half. Kevin Garnett had 20 points and Joe Smith added 18 points and 12 rebounds for the Timberwolves, who won their fourth straight after going winless during a three-game West Coast road trip. Danny Fortson scored 17 points, 13 on free throws, and had 14 rebounds for the Warriors, who have lost seven of their last eight games. Bob Sura had 16 points and Hughes added 14. "I think the second half, we wanted to come out and assert ourselves and we did that," said Garnett, who didn't play in the fourth quarter. "It's a great sign that we can have guys on the bench come in and finish the game." Minnesota had plenty of help from Golden State, which committed 20 turnovers on the night, three days after committing 24 in a loss at Utah. The Wolves scored 25 points off turnovers. "We started throwing the ball away," Cowens said. "That loosened up their shooters big-time because there wasn't any pressure on them." Golden State was 30-for-79 from the floor for 38 percent and went 23-for-31 from the free-throw line. "When you shoot like that, you've got to hope the other team shoots as bad as you do," Fortson said.

Game notes
Timberwolves G Felipe Lopez walked off the court midway through the second quarter after hitting the floor hard when he went up for a rebound. Lopez, averaging 7.2 minutes a game, said he thinks he hurt his upper groin. ... Minnesota's Terrell Brandon leads the league in free-throw percentage, going 49-for-50 from the line this season. He made his only attempt Tuesday night. ... Minnesota is 4-1 in the front half of back-to-back games this season, but 2-2 on the tail end. The Timberwolves play at Utah on Wednesday night.
